---
import CalloutSection from '../CalloutSection.astro';
import BookSampleForm from '../BookSampleForm.astro';
---

<div class="page-shell">
  <section class="hero-section">
    <div class="hero-content">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="h3">
          We're drowning in products nobody wants, built by people who never asked if they should.
        </p>
        <p class="h3">
          Every day, thousands of new apps, websites, and digital products launch. Most will be forgotten within six months—not because they don't work, but because nobody needed them in the first place.
        </p>
        <h1 class="h1 text-accent mt-20 mb-4">Products People<br />Actually Want</h1>
        <h2 class="h2">A practical guide to building better products.</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="overview-section mt-20">
    <div class="overview-intro">

      <div class="body-copy">
        <p class="h3">
          Based on 25+ years of experience consulting for companies like IKEA, Herman Miller, Loom, Google, and Spotify, this book covers everything from user research and stakeholder communication to design systems and team leadership.
        </p>
        <p class="h3">
          Learn how to focus on what users actually need, communicate design decisions effectively, and build products people genuinely want to use.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <CalloutSection className="learning-callout" title="You'll learn">
      <div class="learning-columns">
        <ul class="body-xxl font-serif learning-list">
          <li>Why "everyone is a designer" and how to leverage diverse perspectives in your team</li>
          <li>The complete product design process that works in the real world, not just in case studies</li>
          <li>How to communicate design decisions and influence stakeholders who "prefer the other option because it looks more modern"</li>
        </ul>
        <ul class="body-xxl font-serif learning-list">
          <li>Practical frameworks for user research that reveal what people actually need (not what they say they want)</li>
          <li>How to design for anyone without falling into the "design for everyone" trap</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CalloutSection>

    <div class="insight-callout">
      <p class="body-xxl font-serif">This isn't another book about making things pretty.</p>
      <p class="body-xxl font-serif">It's about understanding humans well enough to build products people actually want.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="toc-section">
    <h2 class="h2">Everything in the book</h2>
    <div class="toc-grid">
      <article class="toc-column">
        <h3 class="h4">Part 1: Understanding product design</h3>
        <ul class="body-sm">
          <li>What product design actually means</li>
          <li>Why everyone makes design decisions</li>
          <li>Product design as a problem solver</li>
          <li>Beyond the screen</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="toc-column">
        <h3 class="h4">Part 2: Building your practice</h3>
        <ul class="body-sm">
          <li>The reality of product design work</li>
          <li>Being the only designer</li>
          <li>Leading without losing your craft</li>
          <li>User research and stakeholder interviews</li>
          <li>Creating a UX strategy</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="toc-column">
        <h3 class="h4">Part 3: The craft</h3>
        <ul class="body-sm">
          <li>The product design process</li>
          <li>Design principles</li>
          <li>Creating meaningful design systems</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="toc-column">
        <h3 class="h4">Part 4: Communication &amp; influence</h3>
        <ul class="body-sm">
          <li>Why designers need to write</li>
          <li>Using writing to think through problems</li>
          <li>How to sell design</li>
          <li>Why designers need to speak business</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="toc-column">
        <h3 class="h4">Part 5: Designing for humans</h3>
        <ul class="body-sm">
          <li>Building emotional relationships with users</li>
          <li>Designing for anyone</li>
          <li>Going beyond good enough</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="testimonials-section">
    <h2 class="h2">What readers say about the book</h2>
    <div class="testimonials-grid">
      <article class="testimonial-card">
        <h3 class="h4">"This book captures what most product design resources miss: the human relationships that make or break building great products."</h3>
        <div class="testimonial-copy">
          <p class="body-lg">This book captures what most product design resources miss: the human relationships that make or break building great products.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">Anton's practical approach to everything from user research to internal communication reads like advice from a trusted mentor. I wish I'd had this book earlier in my career.</p>
        </div>
        <footer class="testimonial-meta">
          <p class="body-sm text-primary font-medium">Kevin Twohy</p>
          <p class="body-sm text-muted">Principal Designer, Twohy Design Works</p>
        </footer>
      </article>

      <article class="testimonial-card">
        <h3 class="h4">"If you're tired of design books that talk in circles, this one actually addresses the work as it is."</h3>
        <div class="testimonial-copy">
          <p class="body-lg">Products People Actually Want is the rare design book that cuts through the noise and gets to the heart of what matters: designing for real people.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">Anton Sten is direct about the realities of product design: the messy trade-offs, the pressure to ship, the challenge of balancing business goals with actual user needs.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">There's a practical honesty here, especially in the way the book calls out feature bloat and the tendency to confuse activity with progress. If you're tired of design books that talk in circles, this one actually addresses the work as it is.</p>
        </div>
        <footer class="testimonial-meta">
          <p class="body-sm text-primary font-medium">Fedor Shkliarau</p>
          <p class="body-sm text-muted">Author of Product Design Portfolio Final Final</p>
        </footer>
      </article>

      <article class="testimonial-card">
        <h3 class="h4">"Anton's nailed it — this is the guide every Product Designer wishes they had."</h3>
        <div class="testimonial-copy">
          <p class="body-lg">Anton's nailed it — this is the guide every Product Designer wishes they had. It's practical, super relevant for 2025 and honestly the stuff UX schools should have been teaching us all along!</p>
        </div>
        <footer class="testimonial-meta">
          <p class="body-sm text-primary font-medium">Buzz Usborne</p>
          <p class="body-sm text-muted">Principal Designer &amp; Coach</p>
        </footer>
      </article>

      <article class="testimonial-card">
        <h3 class="h4">"A design mentor in book-form"</h3>
        <div class="testimonial-copy">
          <p class="body-lg">What I like about this book is that it's an easy read that talks about design in a holistic way.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">It's a book I wish I read at the beginning of my career, because it really shows the many facets that make up design and underlines it with personal stories, concrete examples and practical tips.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">Now reading this book further into my career it still is insightful - but also just very relatable and reassuring. Truly a design mentor in book-form.</p>
        </div>
        <footer class="testimonial-meta">
          <p class="body-sm text-primary font-medium">Maureen Herben</p>
          <p class="body-sm text-muted">Senior designer, Typeform</p>
        </footer>
      </article>

      <article class="testimonial-card">
        <h3 class="h4">"This book is sharp, grounded, and unflinching - a reminder that success isn't about features, it's about outcomes that matter."</h3>
        <div class="testimonial-copy">
          <p class="body-lg">Most design books are written from the sidelines. This one is written from the arena. Anton's Products People Actually Want is built on hard-won lessons from real projects where the stakes were high and the consequences of getting it wrong were huge.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">What makes this book stand out is its honesty. It doesn't dress design up in theory or shiny frameworks. It lays bare the real, messy, human work of building products people care about. I've worked with Anton on high-stakes projects for major brands, and I've seen firsthand how he moves seamlessly from detail to strategy without ever losing sight of the human at the center.</p>
          <p class="body-lg">This book is sharp, grounded, and unflinching - a reminder that success isn't about features, it's about outcomes that matter. Every designer, PM, and founder who reads it will come away changed.</p>
        </div>
        <footer class="testimonial-meta">
          <p class="body-sm text-primary font-medium">Sharif Matar</p>
          <p class="body-sm text-muted">Design Leader</p>
        </footer>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pricing-section">
    <div class="pricing-intro">
      <h2 class="h2">Ready to build products people actually want?</h2>
      <p class="body-xxl font-serif">
        I'm not here to oversell you or make you second-guess with a dozen different options and add-ons.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="pricing-grid">
      <article class="pricing-card">
        <div class="pricing-header">
          <h3 class="h4">E-book</h3>
          <p class="pricing-price">$29</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="pricing-features body-lg">
          <li>✓ Book in PDF and ePub format</li>
          <li>✓ Access to Slack community</li>
        </ul>
        <a
          href="https://antonsten.lemonsqueezy.com/buy/3fd0b9b0-239d-479d-a0bc-db13b45f143d?media=0&logo=0"
          class="pricing-cta"
          onclick="trackBookPurchase('E-book', 29)"
        >
          Get e-book
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="pricing-card">
        <div class="pricing-header">
          <h3 class="h4">Physical book</h3>
          <p class="pricing-price">$29</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="pricing-features body-lg">
          <li>✓ Physical paperback book</li>
          <li>✓ Access to Slack community</li>
          <li>✓ Available on Amazon worldwide</li>
        </ul>
        <a
          href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FXMY87SY"
          id="amazon-buy-link"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="pricing-cta"
          onclick="trackBookPurchase('Physical Book - Amazon', 29)"
        >
          Buy on Amazon
        </a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="author-section">
    <div class="author-grid">
      <div class="author-copy">
        <h2 class="h2">About me</h2>
        <div class="author-body">
          <p class="body-xxl font-serif">
            I've spent the past 25+ years designing and consulting for companies like IKEA, Herman Miller, Loom, Google, and Spotify. Right now, I'm Head of Design at Summer Health.
          </p>
          <p class="body-xxl font-serif">
            Along the way, my writing has found its way into the design community, and I've had the chance to speak at conferences and design schools around the world.
          </p>
          <p class="body-xxl font-serif">
            I'm based in Sweden, where I split my time between building products that matter, writing about design, and taking long walks with my wife and our dog, Taylor.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <img
        src="/images/anton-taylor-cph.webp"
        alt="Anton Sten"
        class="author-image"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="sample-section" id="free-sample">
    <CalloutSection
      title="See what the book is about"
      background="rgb(var(--color-accent-soft))"
      className="sample-callout"
    >
      <BookSampleForm
        description=""
        buttonText="Get free chapters"
        successMessage="Check your email for the download link!"
        variant="callout"
      />
    </CalloutSection>
  </section>
</div>

